<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-131-630  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 131 630.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Canadian Datasystems  Feb 1989 v21 n2 p76(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Why we need a virus control centre. (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dewdney, Alexander.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The computer worm that caused such consternation on Nov 2, 1988when it attacked the computers in the vast Internet system pointedout the need for cooperative centralized measures to combat theseattempts.andP;  The Internet worm invaded at least a thousand computersin only hours.andP;  Users at infected installations saw memory spacebeing soaked up by unknown processes.andP;  System response sloweduntil some directors were forced to shut down.andP;  In the future theindustry may face an endless round of viruses, well-thought-outdefenses, and more advanced viruses that can penetrate thosedefenses.andP;  Prevention can only go so far.andP;  What may be morevaluable is ad hoc remedies such as a Centre for Computer VirusControl staffed with people who can respond quickly to computeremergencies.andP;  The centre could also act in an educative andconsultative capacity.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer VirusesEmergenciesComputer CrimesCentralizationSecurity.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>